{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionIn recent years, computer-aided synthesis planning (CASP) [1][2][3][4] has emerged as an automatic approach for designing synthesis routes of new chemicals [5,6].",
    "This development has been facilitated by extensive research on predicting retrosynthesis steps [7][8][9][10] and the algorithms that guide machines in finding the most suitable synthetic pathways [11][12][13].",
    "However, an important consideration when carrying out actual synthesis in the laboratory is the selection of proper reaction conditions to maximize yields for each reaction.",
    "This consideration is crucial for reducing the cost of purification and maximizing the overall yield of the synthesis route leading to the final product [14][15][16].",
    "By suggesting suitable reaction conditions such as reagent, solvent, and catalyst, CASP can help researchers save time and resources in their quest for more efficient and effective reactions."
  ]
}